You are an expert front-end designer and CSS architect.

Goal
Design a custom, modern CSS stylesheet (no frameworks, no prebuilt Hugo themes) for the homepage of an EV charging business called **Boost**. This stylesheet will be used in a Hugo site for the landing page only.

Visual inspiration
Use the attached screenshots as visual reference (they are from an EV charging company called Orange, but do **not** copy their content or branding). Instead, recreate the same **visual feel**:

- Clean, minimal, lots of white/very light background.
- Slim top navigation bar with logo on the left, nav links in the middle, CTAs (Log in / Contact Sales) on the right.
- Strong, left-aligned hero headline with generous line-height and whitespace.
- Simple, high-contrast CTA button.
- Sections with lots of breathing room, clear grids, subtle icons, and simple line illustrations.
- A calm, ‚Äúpremium but friendly‚Äù SaaS/energy-tech aesthetic.

Branding for Boost
- Company name: **Boost**.
- Use CSS variables for colors so I can tweak later:

  ```css
  :root {
    --boost-bg: #f9fafb;          /* page background */
    --boost-surface: #ffffff;     /* cards/sections */
    --boost-text: #222222;        /* main text */
    --boost-muted-text: #6b7280;  /* secondary text */
    --boost-accent: #ff5c2b;      /* primary accent (Boost orange) */
    --boost-accent-soft: rgba(255, 92, 43, 0.1);
    --boost-border-subtle: #e5e7eb;
  }
````

* Font: system sans stack similar to Inter / SF Pro / Segoe UI.
* Buttons use `--boost-accent` background with white text and subtle hover states.

Layout requirements
Create CSS that assumes a simple semantic HTML structure for the landing page with these main sections and class names:

1. **Site shell & nav**

   * `.site-header` (fixed top, subtle bottom border, white background).
   * `.nav-bar` as a flex container with:

     * `.nav-logo` (Boost wordmark placeholder).
     * `.nav-links` (horizontal list of links like ‚ÄúWhy Boost?‚Äù, ‚ÄúProducts‚Äù, ‚ÄúSolutions‚Äù, ‚ÄúResources‚Äù).
     * `.nav-actions` (two buttons: ghost ‚ÄúLog in‚Äù, filled ‚ÄúContact sales‚Äù).
   * Make nav responsive: collapse to a simple layout on mobile (stacked or menu button, but keep CSS simple).

2. **Hero section**

   * `.hero` full-width with large vertical padding (e.g. 6‚Äì8rem) and max-width content container (`.container`).
   * Left-aligned copy:

     * `.hero-eyebrow` (small label like ‚ÄúEV charging for multifamily & workplace‚Äù).
     * `.hero-title` (big, bold heading, ~ clamp(2.8rem, 4vw, 3.6rem)).
     * `.hero-subtitle` (muted text, narrower width, good line height).
     * `.hero-actions` with a primary CTA button `.btn-primary` and an optional secondary link.
   * Beneath the text (or overlapping edge) space for a full-width image/video banner `.hero-media` (e.g. cars parked and charging).

3. **Pain points / problems row**

   * Section class: `.section-problems`.
   * Inside: a 4-column responsive grid `.problem-grid` that collapses on mobile.
   * Each item uses `.problem-card` with:

     * `.problem-icon` (simple line icon placeholder).
     * `.problem-title` (short heading, e.g. ‚ÄúHigh capital cost‚Äù).
     * `.problem-body` (short explanation).
   * Style like the reference: light icons, clean text, no heavy borders, maybe subtle top margin between items.

4. **Benefits / reliability accordions**

   * Section class: `.section-benefits`.
   * Two-column layout on desktop: text on left, image/video on right.

     * `.benefits-copy` (left)
     * `.benefits-media` (right, for a product photo).
   * Within `.benefits-copy`, use an accordion or expandable list style:

     * Parent label like `.section-label` (‚ÄúReliability‚Äù or ‚ÄúSimplicity‚Äù) in accent color.
     * Each row `.benefit-item` has:

       * `.benefit-header` (title + ‚Äú+‚Äù icon).
       * `.benefit-body` (hidden by default; style as if it could be revealed).
   * Provide CSS for the accordion states using classes like `.is-open` (the JS will toggle this later).

5. **Simplicity section**

   * Similar two-column split, but with image left & copy right (`.section-simplicity`, `.simplicity-media`, `.simplicity-copy`).
   * Copy uses a small label like ‚ÄúSimplicity‚Äù in accent and feature rows similar to above.

6. **Ecosystem / illustration strip**

   * Wide, light-gray section `.section-ecosystem` with a simple line drawing aesthetic:

     * Basic horizontal layout with parking spots, chargers, scooters, bikes, etc. will be an SVG or image later.
   * CSS should:

     * Center the illustration.
     * Add soft accent ‚Äúhalo‚Äù circles using `box-shadow`/pseudo-elements or allow for PNG/SVG halos.
   * Use subtle top and bottom padding, but keep it airy.

7. **Footer**

   * `.site-footer` with subdued background (`--boost-surface`) and a border top.
   * Space for logo, small nav columns, and legal text.

General CSS rules

* Use a `body` and `.container` pattern:

  ```css
  body {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", sans-serif;
    color: var(--boost-text);
    background-color: var(--boost-bg);
  }

  .container {
    max-width: 1120px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding-inline: 1.5rem;
  }
  ```
* Large vertical spacing between sections: `padding-block: 5rem‚Äì7rem`.
* Consistent heading hierarchy: `h1` hero on[118;1:3uly, `h2` for section titles, `h3` inside cards.
* Buttons:

  * `.btn`, `.btn-primary`, `.btn-ghost`.
  * Rounded corners (6‚Äì999px radius, but not pills), small shadow on hover, slightly darker accent color on hover.
* Cards/tiles: use subtle `box-shadow` or borders, but keep everything very light.
* Icons and illustration halos in accent color with low opacity.

Responsive behavior

* Mobile-first CSS.
* For screens `< 768px`:

  * Stack columns in two-column sections (`flex-direction: column`, media down then text or vice versa).
  * Reduce hero font sizes slightly with `clamp`.
  * Ensure nav doesn‚Äôt overflow; allow wrapping or a simple stack.
* For large screens:

  * Keep hero text max-width around 36‚Äì44rem for readability.
  * Maintain generous margins around imagery.

Output format

1. A single production-ready stylesheet named `boost.css` (no external libraries) using the class names and CSS variables described above.
2. At the end, include a **very small** HTML snippet (no more than ~40‚Äì50 lines) that demonstrates how the classes are expected to be used in a Hugo `index.html` layout (just standard HTML, I‚Äôll add Hugo templating myself). Focus on the hero, nav, one problem card row, and one benefits split section as an example.

Avoid:

* Any reference to the original company‚Äôs name, logo, or copy.
* Using a prebuilt CSS framework (Tailwind, Bootstrap, etc.).
* Overly fancy animations; at most, subtle hover transitions (`transition: 150ms ease` on buttons and links is enough).

Design for **Boost** as a brand: clean, modern, easy to read, with an emphasis on making EV charging simple for residents and property owners.

